‘Comprehensive’: the agenda should mobilize actions from a diversity of actors, including nongovernmental organizations, and marginalized and Indigenous peoples (particularly in the Global South), while facilitating learning across governance levels and regions.

‘Collaborative’: the agenda should involve other UN conventions, scientists and existing initiatives that engage societal actors in the design and implementation of the agenda, including the sharing of mobilization, recording and evaluative functions.

‘Catalytic’: the agenda should inspire societal (nonstate and subnational) actors to take action, and facilitate interfaces between them and governments to reach higher ambition through long-term mobilization and engagement.

AHC will continue its campaign and work with other Schools to allow a larger population of students to learn about #ClimateAction and adopt better practices to fight back #climatechange.

By the end of the session, AHC distributed reusable, environmentally friendly tote bags to the students and provided five different teaching posters to the school on climate change and guidelines for sustainable practices.

In collaboration with Maryamana secondary school in Ankawa, a total of 100 students attended the session and learned about the concepts of Climate Change, how individuals contribute to climate change and the sustainable practices that help adapt to its impacts.
AHC recognizes the importance of raising awareness for the young generations to build a foundation that understands the role of safeguarding our mother nature.
